Heterosexual vaginal intercourse is still the leading rout of transmission 
of HIV world-wide. You're right, male to female transmission is higher than 
female to male transmission. In an otherwise healthy adult, the risk of 
female to male transmission is fairly low. But there in lies the rub, most 
HIV+ patients have other STDs - like herpes, HPC or HepC. Those diseases 
are far more likely to transmit female to male relative to HIV. So you end 
up with a titer for one of those, or you share a needle w/ someone and 
you're now immunocompromised. not as easy to fight it off the second time. 
and lets be honest - the kind of people having unprotected sex w/ someone 
they don't know probably aren't first-timers, you know?


then there are issues w/ the localized areas of 
transmission...micro-environment is important and you end up with areas of 
the mucosa that are inflamed and more susceptible.


In reality they don't fully know why sometimes you contract it and other 
times you don't but what is true is the probability itself goes up with 
subsequent encounters. And obviously the risk goes up with more encounters- 
if you play russian roulette 5 times for example. but the risk of each 
individual encounter goes up as well - like playing russian roulette 
without spinning after each shot.
